        <h2 id="freelancer-vs-agency">Freelancer vs agency: what is the real difference?</h2>
        <p>
          This is one of the most common questions small business owners in Ahmedabad ask. Both can produce excellent work. Here is an honest comparison:
        </p>
        <p><strong>Individual freelancer (₹5,000 to ₹30,000 typical range)</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Lower cost for simple sites</li>
          <li>One person handling design, development, and communication</li>
          <li>Availability can be unpredictable (personal situations, workload spikes)</li>
          <li>Limited ongoing support if they become unavailable</li>
          <li>Quality varies widely; verify with live site samples and client references</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Small local agency (₹25,000 to ₹1,50,000 typical range)</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Team approach: designer, developer, and account manager may be different people</li>
          <li>More consistent delivery and communication</li>
          <li>Ongoing support is more reliable</li>
          <li>Can handle larger or more complex projects</li>
          <li>Usually includes project management and structured deliverables</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>National or premium agency (₹1,00,000 to ₹10,00,000+)</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Brand strategy, UX research, and content strategy included</li>
          <li>Dedicated project teams</li>
          <li>Usually overkill for most local businesses unless you have specific complex requirements</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          For most businesses in Gujarat, a trusted local agency or a well-reviewed freelancer with a solid portfolio is the right choice. The key is to verify their work with live URLs, not just screenshots.
        </p>

        <h2 id="what-to-include">What your website should actually include in 2025</h2>
        <p>
          Regardless of price, certain elements are non-negotiable for a business website in 2025. Make sure these are included before you sign anything:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Mobile-first design:</strong> Over 70% of web traffic in India comes from mobile. Your site must work perfectly on phones, not just be "mobile compatible."</li>
          <li><strong>PageSpeed above 80 on mobile:</strong> A slow site loses visitors and ranks poorly in Google. Ask for PageSpeed Insights results before and after launch.</li>
          <li><strong>SSL certificate (HTTPS):</strong> Without this, browsers show a "Not Secure" warning. Non-negotiable.</li>
          <li><strong>Basic on-page SEO:</strong> Proper meta titles, descriptions, heading structure, and image alt text should be set up at launch.</li>
          <li><strong>Google Analytics 4 and Search Console:</strong> You need data from day one. Both are free to set up and should be included.</li>
          <li><strong>Clear calls to action:</strong> Every page should guide a visitor toward calling you, filling a form, or WhatsApp messaging.</li>
          <li><strong>WhatsApp contact button:</strong> In India, WhatsApp is the preferred first contact method for many customers. A floating button is now standard on local business sites.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="red-flags">Red flags when hiring a web designer in India</h2>
        <p>These situations should make you cautious:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No written contract or scope of work:</strong> Verbal agreements lead to scope creep and disputes. Always get a written document listing exactly what will be delivered.</li>
          <li><strong>Asking for 100% payment upfront:</strong> A typical payment structure is 50% to start, 50% on delivery. More than 70% upfront is unusual.</li>
          <li><strong>Cannot show you live website links:</strong> Portfolio screenshots can be fabricated. Always ask for live URLs and test them yourself.</li>
          <li><strong>Guaranteed Google rankings within 30 days:</strong> SEO takes time and cannot be guaranteed. Anyone making this promise is either lying or planning to use black-hat methods.</li>
          <li><strong>Unusually low price with aggressive timeline:</strong> "We can build a 20-page website for 8,000 rupees in 3 days" almost always means a template with your text pasted in, no custom work, and no SEO consideration.</li>
          <li><strong>They own your domain or hosting account:</strong> Always ensure your domain is registered in your name. If a designer holds these, you have no leverage when the relationship ends.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="getting-right-price">How to get the right price for your website</h2>
        <p>
          Before approaching any designer or agency, prepare a brief that answers these questions:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>How many pages does your site need?</li>
          <li>Do you need e-commerce functionality?</li>
          <li>Who will provide the text and images? (you or the agency)</li>
          <li>What is the primary goal of the website? (leads, sales, bookings, information)</li>
          <li>Do you have an existing brand identity (logo, colours, fonts)?</li>
          <li>What is your monthly budget for ongoing maintenance?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          With this brief ready, get at least three quotes from different providers. Do not automatically choose the cheapest. Compare what each quote includes: domain, hosting, content, SEO setup, post-launch support, training, and revisions.
        </p>
        <p>
          A website is not a one-time expense. It is an ongoing business asset. The right investment is one that generates leads, builds credibility, and can be maintained and updated as your business grows.
        </p>

